      "difficulty": "medium",
      "questionText": "Sketch the curve $y = x^2 - 4x - 5$.\nOn your sketch, label:\n(a) the coordinates of the $y$-intercept,\n(b) the coordinates of the $x$-intercepts (roots),\n(c) the coordinates of the turning point.",
      "answerType": "draw",
      "correctAnswer": "$y$-int: $(0,-5)$; roots: $(5,0)$ and $(-1,0)$; turning point: $(2,-9)$",
      "tolerance": null,
      "unit": null,
      "markScheme": [
        { "mark": "B1", "desc": "$y$-intercept $(0,-5)$" },
        { "mark": "B1", "desc": "Roots $(-1,0)$ and $(5,0)$" },
        { "mark": "M1", "desc": "Turning point $x = \\frac{-1+5}{2} = 2$" },
        { "mark": "A1", "desc": "Turning point $(2,-9)$; upward parabola shape" }
      ],
      "workingSteps": [
        "(a) $y$-intercept: set $x=0$: $y=-5$; point $(0,-5)$",
        "(b) Roots: $x^2-4x-5=0 \\Rightarrow (x-5)(x+1)=0 \\Rightarrow x=5$ or $x=-1$",
        "(c) Turning point: $x = \\frac{-(-4)}{2(1)} = \\frac{4}{2} = 2$; $y=4-8-5=-9$; point $(2,-9)$",
        "Check factorisation: $(x-5)(x+1)=x^2-4x-5$ ✓"
      ],
      "explanation": "For $y=ax^2+bx+c$: $y$-int at $(0,c)$; roots by factorisation or formula; vertex at $x=-b/(2a)$."
    },
